The 'Ruler' procedure displays a repeating sequence of ascending digits starting from 1, of any length, at some selectiable location on your screen. 
In nother words, you can display a string of digits anywhere you'd like.

This might allow you to determine where in the horizontal dimension of the console window a line begins or some character falls. 
The 'Ruler' procedure enables you to specify how long the displayed ruler is, in digits, and where on the screen it will be displayed. 

A typical call to 'Ruler' would look something like this below: 

	mov eax, 1		; Load Y position to AL 
	mov ebx, 1 		; Load X position to BL 
	mov ecx, COLS-1		; Load ruler length to ECX
	call Ruler 		; Write the ruler to the buffer 

This invocatino places a ruler at the upper-left corner of the display, beginning at position 1,1. 
The length of the ruler is passed in ECX. 
Here, you're specifying a ruler one character shorter than the display is wide. 
This provides a ruler that spans the full visible width of your virtual text display

Why on character shorter?
Remember that there is an EOL character at the end of every line. 
This EOL character isn't visible directly, but it's still a character and requires a byte in the buffer to hold it. 
The 'COLS' equate must always take this into account: if you wnat an 80-character wide display, 'COLS' must be set to 81. 
If you want a 96-character wide display, 'COLS' must be set to 97.
If you code a call to 'Ruler' as shown above, NASM will do some assembly-time math and always generate ruler that spans the full (visible) width of the text display.

Over and above the 'LOOP' instructions, there's a fair amount of new assembly technology at work here that could stand explaining. 

